[SPEAKER_16]: But as a man of religious bent that I hold myself to be, I have no other course left open to me.

203
00:41:37,189 --> 00:41:46,713
[SPEAKER_16]: As I have said in my letter to Sir Samuel Hoare, even if His Majesty's government decided to release me in order to save themselves embarrassment, my fast will have to continue.

204
00:41:47,573 --> 00:41:57,698
[SPEAKER_16]: for I cannot now hope to resist the decision by any other means, and I have no desire whatsoever to compass my release by any means other than honorable.

205
00:41:58,399 --> 00:42:07,924
[SPEAKER_16]: It may be that my judgment is warped, and that I'm wholly in error in regarding separate electorates for the depressed classes as harmful to them or Hinduism.

206
00:42:08,744 --> 00:42:14,149
[SPEAKER_16]: If so, I am not likely to be in the right with reference to other parts of my philosophy of life.

207
00:42:14,989 --> 00:42:26,559
[SPEAKER_16]: In that case, my death by fasting will at once be a penance for my error and a lifting of a weight from off those numberless men and women who have a childlike faith in my wisdom.

208
00:42:27,520 --> 00:42:41,838
[SPEAKER_16]: Whereas if my judgment is right, as I have little doubt it is, the contemplated step is but a due fulfillment of the scheme of life which I have tried for more than a quarter of a century, apparently not without considerable success.

209
00:42:52,436 --> 00:42:58,219
[SPEAKER_12]: 6 October 1983, the Commissioner of Prisons, Pretoria.

210
00:42:59,459 --> 00:43:17,827
[SPEAKER_12]: Sir, we have been informed by the local authorities that in accordance with an instruction from prison headquarters, prisoners who are taken to doctors, hospitals, courts, et cetera, will in future be handcuffed and put in leg irons.

211
00:43:19,188 --> 00:43:23,910
[SPEAKER_12]: We are told that this is to be applied to all prisoners, i.e.

212
00:43:23,970 --> 00:43:27,892
[SPEAKER_12]: security prisoners as well as common law prisoners.

213
00:43:29,753 --> 00:43:41,038
[SPEAKER_12]: We wish to make an earnest appeal to you to reconsider your decision relating to security prisoners and allow the present position to continue.

214
00:43:42,859 --> 00:43:49,765
[SPEAKER_12]: During the 20 years that we have spent in prison, there have been numerous changes in our treatment.

215
00:43:51,027 --> 00:44:01,356
[SPEAKER_12]: Previously, we had been handcuffed when we were taken from Robben Island to Cape Town, but for a number of years, this has been discontinued.

216
00:44:02,536 --> 00:44:16,141
[SPEAKER_12]: We welcomed and appreciated the discontinuance as we welcomed all changes that were designed to alleviate the hardships of prison life and make our stay more tolerable.

217
00:44:17,681 --> 00:44:29,665
[SPEAKER_12]: Of special concern to us was the removal of practices which were not only outdated, but which were unnecessarily burdensome and humiliating.

218
00:44:31,511 --> 00:44:43,961
[SPEAKER_12]: While we do not wish to comment on the general security arrangements of the Prisons Department, we nevertheless wish to make some observations in support of our present appeal.

219
00:44:45,662 --> 00:44:45,742
[SPEAKER_12]: One.

220
00:44:46,883 --> 00:45:06,760
[SPEAKER_12]: To the best of our knowledge, during the entire period of our incarceration, there has not been a single instance where a security prisoner has escaped or even attempted to do so while being escorted to Cape Town for medical reasons.

221
00:45:08,515 --> 00:45:24,650
[SPEAKER_12]: Two, for the year and a half that we have been at POSMA, our experience has been that each time any of us was taken out, he was invariably accompanied by four or more warders, some armed.

222
00:45:25,771 --> 00:45:30,335
[SPEAKER_12]: Often the warders were accompanied by a member of security police.

223
00:45:32,284 --> 00:45:44,078
[SPEAKER_12]: Three, this elaborate arrangement has been strictly applied in spite of our advanced ages and physical condition.

224
00:45:47,958 --> 00:46:01,745
[SPEAKER_12]: Four, in our opinion, such arrangements were and still remain quite adequate, and the additional restraints are totally unwarranted, burdensome, and humiliating.

225
00:46:02,845 --> 00:46:12,630
[SPEAKER_12]: This is aggravated by the great deal of attention and curiosity that is aroused among the public at the sight of handcuffed prisoners.

226
00:46:14,668 --> 00:46:30,548
[SPEAKER_12]: Five, we are certain that Robben Island and Palsmo authorities will be able to bear out our contention that security prisoners could not be accused of having abused the medical outings.

227
00:46:32,393 --> 00:46:48,228
[SPEAKER_12]: Six, it has been pointed out to us and recently with greater emphasis that there is no distinction in the treatment of prisoners irrespective of whether they are common law or security prisoners.

228
00:46:50,752 --> 00:47:00,365
[SPEAKER_12]: 7.

229
00:46:52,134 --> 00:47:00,365
[SPEAKER_12]: With respect, sir, may we remind you that this is not strictly in accordance with the factual position.

230
00:47:01,126 --> 00:47:07,114
[SPEAKER_12]: For example, security prisoners are denied the privilege of contact visits.

231
00:47:07,955 --> 00:47:17,023
[SPEAKER_12]: And generally, even though they may be classified as A-groups, they suffer from restrictions in their day-to-day stay.

232
00:47:17,984 --> 00:47:28,533
[SPEAKER_12]: Perhaps more important, security prisoners on the whole are being denied the facilities for remission and parole enjoyed by other prisoners.

233
00:47:30,045 --> 00:47:39,931
[SPEAKER_12]: We believe that the few to whom this dispensation was extended were given remission ranging from a couple of weeks to a few months.

234
00:47:41,972 --> 00:47:58,302
[SPEAKER_12]: Eight, we submit that since differential treatment does in fact exist, there should be no reason why security prisoners should not be exempted from the instructions regarding handcuffs and leg irons.

235
00:48:00,345 --> 00:48:10,392
[SPEAKER_12]: Nine, lastly, from the point of view of health, we consider these new arrangements to be a decided disadvantage.

236
00:48:11,693 --> 00:48:14,875
[SPEAKER_12]: A number of us are suffering from high blood pressure.

237
00:48:15,775 --> 00:48:24,221
[SPEAKER_12]: And it is important that when we are taken to specialists, we should be relaxed and completely free of tension.

238
00:48:25,918 --> 00:48:34,526
[SPEAKER_12]: it is likely that the humiliation and resentment caused by handcuffs will adversely affect our blood pressure.

239
00:48:35,627 --> 00:48:42,934
[SPEAKER_12]: To an extent, therefore, this could be defeating the purpose of us consulting the specialists.

240
00:48:44,785 --> 00:48:54,688
[SPEAKER_12]: We respectfully state that we cannot think of a single valid reason why this new restriction should be applied to us.

241
00:48:55,488 --> 00:49:00,110
[SPEAKER_12]: And we, once again, appeal to you to abandon them.

242
00:49:01,430 --> 00:49:01,970
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you.

243
00:49:02,651 --> 00:49:06,812
[SPEAKER_12]: Yours faithfully, Nelson Rohilala Mandela.

244
00:49:15,678 --> 00:49:19,347
[SPEAKER_07]: excerpted from Reverend Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'

245
00:49:19,327 --> 00:49:22,113
[SPEAKER_07]: 's letter from the Birmingham jail, April 16, 1963.

246
00:49:25,652 --> 00:49:28,934
[SPEAKER_07]: You may well ask, why direct action?

247
00:49:29,735 --> 00:49:32,216
[SPEAKER_07]: Why sit-ins, marches, and so forth?

248
00:49:33,117 --> 00:49:35,298
[SPEAKER_07]: Isn't negotiation a better path?

249
00:49:36,519 --> 00:49:39,141
[SPEAKER_07]: You are quite right in calling for negotiation.

250
00:49:39,221 --> 00:49:42,443
[SPEAKER_07]: Indeed, this is the very purpose of direct action.

251
00:49:43,223 --> 00:49:46,085
[SPEAKER_07]: Nonviolent, direct action seeks to create

252
00:49:49,132 --> 00:49:57,978
[SPEAKER_07]: such a crisis and fosters such a tension that a community which has constantly refused to negotiate is forced to confront the issue.

253
00:49:58,999 --> 00:50:03,222
[SPEAKER_07]: It seeks to so dramatize the issue that it can no longer be ignored.

254
00:50:04,636 --> 00:50:16,405
[SPEAKER_07]: My citing the creation of tension as part of the work of the Nonviolent Resistor may sound rather shocking, but I must confess that I am not afraid of the word tension.

255
00:50:17,286 --> 00:50:26,873
[SPEAKER_07]: I have earnestly opposed violent tension, but there is a type of constructive nonviolent tension which is necessary for growth.

256
00:50:28,130 --> 00:50:57,109
[SPEAKER_07]: Just as Socrates felt that it was necessary to create tension in the mind so that individuals could rise from the bondage of myths and half-truths to the unfettered realm of creative analysis and objective appraisal, so must we see the need for nonviolent gadflies to create the kind of tension in society that will help men rise from the dark depths of prejudice and racism to the majestic heights of understanding and brotherhood.

257
00:50:58,090 --> 00:51:09,222
[SPEAKER_07]: The purpose of our direct action program is to create a situation so crisis-packed that it will invariably and inevitably open the door to negotiation.

258
00:51:10,103 --> 00:51:13,727
[SPEAKER_07]: I therefore concur with you in your call for negotiation.

259
00:51:14,463 --> 00:51:22,448
[SPEAKER_07]: Too long has our beloved Southland been bogged down in a tragic effort to live in monologue rather than in dialogue.

260
00:51:23,409 --> 00:51:30,834
[SPEAKER_07]: One of the basic points in your statement is that the action that I and my associates have taken in Birmingham is untimely.

261
00:51:31,555 --> 00:51:36,478
[SPEAKER_07]: Some have asked, why didn't you give this new city administration time to act?

262
00:51:37,470 --> 00:51:48,675
[SPEAKER_07]: The only answer that I can give to this query is that the new Birmingham administration must be prodded about as much as the outgoing one before it will act.

263
00:51:49,675 --> 00:51:56,859
[SPEAKER_07]: We are sadly mistaken if we feel that the elevation of Albert Boutwell as mayor will bring the millennium to Birmingham.

264
00:51:57,419 --> 00:52:04,002
[SPEAKER_07]: While Mr. Boutwell is a much more gentle person than Mr. Connor, they are both segregationists.

265
00:52:06,101 --> 00:52:08,522
[SPEAKER_07]: dedicated to the maintenance of the status quo.

266
00:52:09,082 --> 00:52:18,608
[SPEAKER_07]: I have hope that Mr. Boutwell will be reasonable enough to see the futility of massive resistance to desegregation.

267
00:52:19,389 --> 00:52:24,112
[SPEAKER_07]: But he will not see this without the pressure from devotees of civil rights.

268
00:52:24,632 --> 00:52:33,678
[SPEAKER_07]: My friends, I must say to you that we have not made a single gain in civil rights without determined legal and nonviolent pressure.

269
00:52:34,258 --> 00:52:41,286
[SPEAKER_07]: Lamentably, it is an historical fact that the privileged groups seldom give up their privileges voluntarily.

270
00:52:42,267 --> 00:52:54,980
[SPEAKER_07]: Individuals may see the moral light and voluntarily give up their unjust posture, but as Reinhold Niebuhr has reminded us, groups tend to be more immoral than individuals.

271
00:52:55,940 --> 00:53:00,062
[SPEAKER_07]: Justice too long delayed is justice denied.

272
00:53:00,882 --> 00:53:06,825
[SPEAKER_07]: We know through painful experience that freedom is never voluntarily given by the oppressor.

273
00:53:07,365 --> 00:53:10,147
[SPEAKER_07]: It must be demanded by the oppressed.

274
00:53:10,847 --> 00:53:16,910
[SPEAKER_07]: Frankly, I have yet to engage in a direct action campaign that was well timed.

275
00:53:18,090 --> 00:53:23,173
[SPEAKER_07]: In the view of those who have not suffered unduly from the disease of segregation,

276
00:53:24,373 --> 00:53:27,274
[SPEAKER_07]: For years now, I have heard the word wait.

277
00:53:28,335 --> 00:53:32,176
[SPEAKER_07]: It rings in the ear of every Negro with piercing familiarity.

278
00:53:32,636 --> 00:53:38,058
[SPEAKER_07]: This wait has almost always meant never.

279
00:53:39,058 --> 00:53:48,482
[SPEAKER_07]: We must come to see with one of our distinguished jurists that justice too long delayed is justice denied.

280
00:55:13,439 --> 00:55:15,580
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, live theater has moving parts.

281
00:55:17,021 --> 00:55:20,522
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you so much Vijaya and Francis.

282
00:55:21,102 --> 00:55:25,664
[SPEAKER_07]: I stand with you in believing that all three civil rights champions changed the world.

283
00:55:26,164 --> 00:55:29,506
[SPEAKER_07]: Their sacrifices are both historic and well documented.

284
00:55:30,026 --> 00:55:36,709
[SPEAKER_07]: Sharing these reflections gives us the opportunity to see Martin Luther King Jr.

285
00:55:37,209 --> 00:55:39,630
[SPEAKER_07]: among his teachers and global contemporaries.

