02:14:10,761 --> 02:14:25,454
[SPEAKER_07]: We're happy to have you with us here today and we appreciate your willingness to join from your home base of Arlington with neighboring West Medford at a time when like minds and hearts really need to work together across city lines.

776
02:14:26,575 --> 02:14:26,935
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

777
02:14:28,897 --> 02:14:29,257
[SPEAKER_08]: Very good.

778
02:14:32,493 --> 02:14:40,117
[SPEAKER_07]: So you may have noticed that today's program has showcased the amazing talents of some wonderful women.

779
02:14:42,899 --> 02:14:44,240
[SPEAKER_07]: That's no accident.

780
02:14:48,562 --> 02:14:53,465
[SPEAKER_07]: Fact of the matter is the movement, quote unquote,

781
02:14:55,619 --> 02:15:06,891
[SPEAKER_07]: was filled to overflowing with the talents and grace and intelligence and dynamism of amazing women.

782
02:15:06,951 --> 02:15:17,462
[SPEAKER_07]: Dr. King was blessed with tremendous relationships with great women who dynamically impacted his work in civil rights and social justice.

783
02:15:18,500 --> 02:15:26,886
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that the West Method Community Center, in fact, has been an incubator of more talented and inspiring women than I can easily recall.

784
02:15:26,946 --> 02:15:32,811
[SPEAKER_07]: I always want to be mindful of such important role models and contributors.

785
02:15:34,165 --> 02:15:36,325
[SPEAKER_07]: So on to the next order of business.

786
02:15:36,405 --> 02:15:43,267
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, it's always a challenge for me to come up with meaningful messages in a keynote address and speaker.

787
02:15:43,787 --> 02:15:48,288
[SPEAKER_07]: Trust me, I've been on both sides, the giving and the receiving end.

788
02:15:51,929 --> 02:15:58,930
[SPEAKER_07]: So this year's selection for a keynote speaker really, really resonates with me.

789
02:15:58,970 --> 02:16:01,911
[SPEAKER_07]: The only concern I had was availability,

790
02:16:02,700 --> 02:16:05,281
[SPEAKER_07]: And that problem worked itself out fairly easily.

791
02:16:05,341 --> 02:16:07,482
[SPEAKER_07]: Kinship always helps in these matters.

792
02:16:09,563 --> 02:16:19,748
[SPEAKER_07]: Celia Johnston Blue is a seasoned executive leader with over 30 years of leadership experience in the private, public, and nonprofit sectors.

793
02:16:20,288 --> 02:16:25,871
[SPEAKER_07]: In 2015, Celia collaborated with 12 women of color from across Massachusetts

794
02:16:26,571 --> 02:16:36,794
[SPEAKER_07]: and led the development and public launch of the Massachusetts Women of Color Coalition, M-A-W-O-C-C, Incorporated.

795
02:16:37,634 --> 02:16:46,657
[SPEAKER_07]: In her current role as president and CEO, she is leading the organization to realize its vision and mission, which

796
02:16:48,775 --> 02:16:56,617
[SPEAKER_07]: is strongly geared toward advocating for the voices of women of color to be heard and to be recognized.

797
02:16:57,257 --> 02:17:08,539
[SPEAKER_07]: Prior to her current role at Maywalk, Celia was the interim director of the Rhode Island Department of Human Services, a cabinet-level position reporting to Governor McKee.

798
02:17:08,899 --> 02:17:14,120
[SPEAKER_07]: Celia led an agency with approximately 1,000 employees in multiple divisions

799
02:17:14,580 --> 02:17:24,783
[SPEAKER_07]: with a budget of approximately $900 million, providing benefits and services to 300,000 or one-third of Rhode Island's population.

800
02:17:25,504 --> 02:17:34,126
[SPEAKER_07]: She spent nine years in the transportation industry here in Massachusetts and gained national experience in multiple modes.

801
02:17:34,186 --> 02:17:39,028
[SPEAKER_07]: First, appointed as a commissioner for the former Massachusetts Aeronautics Commission

802
02:17:39,688 --> 02:17:52,560
[SPEAKER_07]: She was later appointed as Deputy Registrar, Assistant Secretary of the Massachusetts Department of Transportation, and then promoted to Registrar, CEO of the Massachusetts Registry of Motor Vehicles.

803
02:17:53,741 --> 02:17:58,105
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, now take that, just think about that for a second.

804
02:17:59,367 --> 02:18:03,931
[SPEAKER_07]: The Registrar and CEO of the Massachusetts Registry of Motor Vehicles.

805
02:18:05,320 --> 02:18:12,170
[SPEAKER_07]: She is the first African-American in Massachusetts history to serve as that registrar for the Commonwealth.

806
02:18:12,230 --> 02:18:14,314
[SPEAKER_07]: She holds a Bachelor of Science degree.

807
02:18:14,434 --> 02:18:14,874
[SPEAKER_07]: That's right.

808
02:18:14,935 --> 02:18:15,696
[SPEAKER_07]: That's worth a clap.

809
02:18:20,243 --> 02:18:30,250
[SPEAKER_07]: a bachelor of science degree from Worcester State University, a master's degree in business administration from Anna Maria College, and is currently enrolled in the Ph.D.

810
02:18:30,290 --> 02:18:32,992
[SPEAKER_07]: leadership program at the University of Vermont.

811
02:18:33,472 --> 02:18:40,797
[SPEAKER_07]: She has received awards for her leadership and commitment to diversity, equity, and inclusion, and was named in the Power 50

812
02:18:41,818 --> 02:18:44,939
[SPEAKER_07]: Class of 2021 by the Worcester Business Journal.

813
02:18:45,299 --> 02:18:51,921
[SPEAKER_07]: And in 2023, she received the Distinguished Alumnae Award from the Worcester State University.

814
02:18:51,961 --> 02:18:58,283
[SPEAKER_07]: Ladies and gentlemen, I present and please give a warm West Medford welcome to Celia Johnston Blue.

815
02:19:21,988 --> 02:19:22,970
[SPEAKER_11]: Good morning.

816
02:19:22,990 --> 02:19:24,953
[SPEAKER_11]: Oh, come on.

817
02:19:24,973 --> 02:19:28,139
[SPEAKER_11]: I know we just ate, but good morning.

818
02:19:28,159 --> 02:19:29,942
[SPEAKER_11]: All right, there we go.

819
02:19:29,962 --> 02:19:31,585
[SPEAKER_11]: Can you guys hear me OK?

820
02:19:36,987 --> 02:19:40,068
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you so much for having me today.

821
02:19:40,088 --> 02:20:05,380
[SPEAKER_11]: I want to recognize the executive director, Linda Grossman, board president, Melinda Regan, board members, the mayor of Medford, other dignitaries, Rafael Parish Center, and the sponsors, staff, planning committee, and all the volunteers that made today's event possible.

822
02:20:06,320 --> 02:20:16,704
[SPEAKER_11]: I want to give a special shout out to Terry Carter, who asked me to speak today, and to you, the audience, for being here today.

823
02:20:17,144 --> 02:20:20,566
[SPEAKER_11]: So I say we give ourselves a round of applause for that.

824
02:20:26,188 --> 02:20:34,731
[SPEAKER_11]: I also want to recognize the awardees today for your work and your commitment, and stay strong and keep moving forward.

825
02:20:37,172 --> 02:20:52,938
[SPEAKER_11]: I want to acknowledge the fact that West Medford Community Center has been providing services and programs and activities and connecting people from West Medford, Mystic River Valley for over 90 years.

826
02:20:53,519 --> 02:20:54,859
[SPEAKER_11]: Congratulations.

827
02:20:54,879 --> 02:20:56,720
[SPEAKER_11]: That is quite an accomplishment.

828
02:21:00,440 --> 02:21:11,727
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm going to start by telling you just a little bit about who I am because I think that's important so that you can see the lens in which I am coming from and how it drives my work.

829
02:21:12,587 --> 02:21:15,129
[SPEAKER_11]: I am very much the immigrant story.

830
02:21:15,889 --> 02:21:20,292
[SPEAKER_11]: My family is from Jamaica, an island in the Caribbean, West Indies.

831
02:21:20,952 --> 02:21:29,097
[SPEAKER_11]: Jamaica was owned and colonized by the Spaniards and English folks like the United States and so many other countries.

832
02:21:30,143 --> 02:21:38,491
[SPEAKER_11]: My family's roots and our lineage, black, West Indian, Scottish, and Irish, and I am still learning about my lineage.

833
02:21:39,412 --> 02:21:51,263
[SPEAKER_11]: I am a mom, a wife, a sister, an auntie, godmother, friend, a boss, and proud daughter of Barrington and Valerie Johnston.

834
02:21:52,930 --> 02:22:05,663
[SPEAKER_11]: My family migrated to Jamaica, from Jamaica to this country, when I was 11 and a half years old, made possible by my Aunt Dorothy Vassell, my father's sister, whom we call the matriarch of our family.

835
02:22:05,683 --> 02:22:10,628
[SPEAKER_11]: I didn't know about racism until I came to the United States.

836
02:22:11,109 --> 02:22:13,751
[SPEAKER_11]: Although I experienced racism, I am grateful.

837
02:22:14,492 --> 02:22:24,462
[SPEAKER_11]: that I also had a positive experience where some of my classmates were kind and open to this young Jamaican girl that came to their school.

838
02:22:25,784 --> 02:22:36,695
[SPEAKER_11]: Fast forward to now, I have a few decades of leadership experience stemming as Terry so eloquently introduced me today in many different sectors.

839
02:22:37,335 --> 02:22:42,906
[SPEAKER_11]: And I have been blessed with most of my career to be in senior and executive level roles.

840
02:22:43,046 --> 02:22:46,432
[SPEAKER_11]: And trust me, I still have the scars for that.

841
02:22:47,906 --> 02:22:53,151
[SPEAKER_11]: Many years ago, God placed on my heart to start an organization focused on women of color.

842
02:22:53,692 --> 02:22:59,377
[SPEAKER_11]: As I know firsthand, the inequities that we faced just about on a daily basis.

843
02:23:00,158 --> 02:23:05,263
[SPEAKER_11]: Our organization is fondly called Maywalk.

844
02:23:05,863 --> 02:23:11,929
[SPEAKER_11]: We started with 12 brilliant women from across the commonwealth, and you can find their bios on our website.

845
02:23:13,226 --> 02:23:22,429
[SPEAKER_11]: For those of you who might not be familiar with Maywalk, we are a statewide nonprofit organization, nonpartisan organization, based in Worcester.

846
02:23:23,069 --> 02:23:34,333
[SPEAKER_11]: And our mission is to address racial inequities as it exists for women of color, created by systemic, institutional, internalized, and interpersonal racism.

847
02:23:34,413 --> 02:23:38,495
[SPEAKER_11]: And we wanted to, as founding members, really call that out.

848
02:23:39,195 --> 02:23:46,119
[SPEAKER_11]: We provide programming, training, and we advocate for policies and legislation for a more equitable commonwealth.

849
02:23:46,719 --> 02:23:50,962
[SPEAKER_11]: Our programming includes a leadership track for training and boards and commission.

850
02:23:51,502 --> 02:23:59,467
[SPEAKER_11]: We have an intergenerational leadership academy for women of color and high school girls of color, which includes a one-year mentorship program.

851
02:24:00,227 --> 02:24:13,398
[SPEAKER_11]: We are doing our part to encourage and empower and provide tools and strategies for women for personal and professional growth and advance their career and also inspire the next generation of leaders.

852
02:24:14,338 --> 02:24:22,105
[SPEAKER_11]: With respect to our advocacy work, we have had overall four legislative wins and two ballot question wins.

853
02:24:22,845 --> 02:24:26,669
[SPEAKER_11]: And I'll just speak briefly about two of the wins we had last year.

854
02:24:26,689 --> 02:24:36,038
[SPEAKER_11]: I do want to say that we also were involved in the expansion of voting here in the Commonwealth called the Votes Act.

855
02:24:36,098 --> 02:24:40,322
[SPEAKER_11]: We're involved in it during COVID when we have to rethink about how to vote.

856
02:24:40,902 --> 02:24:47,608
[SPEAKER_11]: We're involved in that movement and then permanently expanding the rights here in the Commonwealth.

857
02:24:48,429 --> 02:24:59,708
[SPEAKER_11]: Last year, the maternity bill got passed, which expands access to midwifery, birth centers, and doula services and addresses postpartum depression.

858
02:25:07,273 --> 02:25:20,668
[SPEAKER_11]: Our ballot questions involve fair share, which is known as the millionaire tax for increased funding to schools and roads and bridges, and the Work and Family Mobility Act, which actually I started working on when I was registrar.

859
02:25:21,469 --> 02:25:27,997
[SPEAKER_11]: It allows immigrants to apply for a driver's license in Massachusetts regardless of their immigration status.

860
02:25:32,657 --> 02:25:41,567
[SPEAKER_11]: And lastly, the Wage Equity Act is when we talk about a piece of the dream, it means also a piece of the economic pie, right?

861
02:25:42,448 --> 02:25:49,796
[SPEAKER_11]: And so last year, we were in the steering committee for passing of the Francis Perkins Workplace Equity Act.

862
02:25:50,376 --> 02:25:53,080
[SPEAKER_11]: This is important for all of us in this room.

863
02:25:53,120 --> 02:25:55,603
[SPEAKER_11]: It goes into effect in June of this year.

864
02:25:56,204 --> 02:25:57,025
[SPEAKER_11]: What does it do?

865
02:25:57,265 --> 02:26:06,116
[SPEAKER_11]: It discloses to the employees who are being offered a promotion or transfer the range of what that position earned.

866
02:26:06,396 --> 02:26:08,159
[SPEAKER_11]: Right now, you don't know that.

867
02:26:08,599 --> 02:26:20,386
[SPEAKER_11]: You can do market research, you can get a sense, but you don't know what that company actually paid, and we know that our white counterparts are being paid more than we are.

868
02:26:21,287 --> 02:26:31,893
[SPEAKER_11]: It also discloses the pay range for anyone who wants to know in your organization what your role earned.

869
02:26:32,887 --> 02:26:43,692
[SPEAKER_11]: It also allows the attorney general to enforce the law for organizations who do not want to cooperate with that.

870
02:26:44,292 --> 02:26:58,798
[SPEAKER_11]: So this is, there's also new pay data reporting obligations, which I think is important, because we don't know if we're not measuring, we don't know how we're doing unless we really have the data to show us how we're doing.

871
02:26:59,638 --> 02:27:04,922
[SPEAKER_11]: So I'm proud to say that we're entering our 10th year, and yes, you can clap for that.

872
02:27:09,725 --> 02:27:16,730
[SPEAKER_11]: And you're all invited to our annual meeting and celebration next Saturday at the Beachwood Hotel in Worcester.

873
02:27:16,770 --> 02:27:20,593
[SPEAKER_11]: You can go online to maywalk.com and register.

874
02:27:20,673 --> 02:27:25,457
[SPEAKER_11]: And I encourage you to become a member and also become an ally and supporter.

875
02:27:26,497 --> 02:27:33,984
[SPEAKER_11]: In preparing for my speech, I went back and listened to many speeches and interviews that Dr. King gave.

876
02:27:34,965 --> 02:27:40,169
[SPEAKER_11]: One of the speeches that he gave to high school students talked about developing a blueprint.

877
02:27:40,689 --> 02:27:41,770
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm going to come back to this.

878
02:27:42,791 --> 02:27:54,054
[SPEAKER_11]: To realize our piece of Dr. King's dream, we must go back to some of the early days of civil rights movement, and we must understand the real history of this country.

879
02:27:54,614 --> 02:28:00,895
[SPEAKER_11]: I would encourage you to listen to this interview that he did in 1967 to NBC.

880
02:28:02,216 --> 02:28:06,237
[SPEAKER_11]: Watching and listening to these many interviews really gave me hope.

881
02:28:06,497 --> 02:28:12,198
[SPEAKER_11]: I was inspired, and it also affirmed our reality as black people that we cannot ignore.

882
02:28:13,438 --> 02:28:21,900
[SPEAKER_11]: Of course, I listened to his famous speech, I Have a Dream speech, but what I'm gonna do is focus on this particular interview.

883
02:28:23,100 --> 02:28:38,542
[SPEAKER_11]: The title of it says, in this rarely seen interview, King speaks bluntly about the new phase of the struggle for genuine equality and his continuous commitment to the civil rights movement.

884
02:28:39,523 --> 02:28:41,703
[SPEAKER_11]: The question that was posed to him was this,

885
02:28:42,323 --> 02:29:06,076
[SPEAKER_11]: Isn't it part of the dilemma now that people know that Negroes were being denied what was guaranteed by the Constitution, by the fact that they were citizens of this country, that when they were given those rights, did you feel like the white community said, well, we have given them all that we have now, and it's up to them?

886
02:29:07,437 --> 02:29:10,160
[SPEAKER_11]: Dr. King answered that the dilemma was deeper.

887
02:29:10,180 --> 02:29:17,648
[SPEAKER_11]: He was saying that the movement was in a transition period where we must be honest with America.

888
02:29:17,668 --> 02:29:23,655
[SPEAKER_11]: Honesty tells me to admit that America has broad racist elements.

889
02:29:25,332 --> 02:29:26,132
[SPEAKER_11]: that exists.

890
02:29:27,533 --> 02:29:31,075
[SPEAKER_11]: Racism is still alive and exists in American society.

891
02:29:31,175 --> 02:29:41,040
[SPEAKER_11]: There has never been a single, solid, determined commitment of large segments of white America on the whole question of racial equality.

892
02:29:41,881 --> 02:29:49,065
[SPEAKER_11]: We have to see that vacillation has always exists, and ambivalence has always exists.

893
02:29:49,585 --> 02:29:52,907
[SPEAKER_11]: And this, to me, is the so-called white backlash.

894
02:29:53,587 --> 02:29:56,650
[SPEAKER_11]: is merely a new name for an old phenomenon.

895
02:29:57,390 --> 02:30:12,322
[SPEAKER_11]: I see the white-black backlash is a continuum in the same ambivalence and facilitation of white America and the whole question of racial justice that has existed since the founding of our nation.

896
02:30:13,263 --> 02:30:31,136
[SPEAKER_11]: We must see that in many of the people that supported us in Selma and Birmingham were outraged about the extremist behaviors towards Negro, but they were not at that moment, and they are not now, committed to genuine equality for Negroes.

897
02:30:31,837 --> 02:30:41,664
[SPEAKER_11]: It is much easier to integrate a lunch counter than it is to guarantee an annual income, for instance, to get rid of poverty for Negroes and poor people.

898
02:30:42,384 --> 02:30:52,192
[SPEAKER_11]: It's much easier to integrate a bus than it is to make genuine integration a reality and quality education a reality in our schools.

899
02:30:52,273 --> 02:30:58,298
[SPEAKER_11]: It is much easier to integrate a public park than getting rid of public slums.

900
02:30:58,958 --> 02:31:08,846
[SPEAKER_11]: We are in a new phase where we've moved from the struggle for decency, characterized the struggle of about 10 to 12 years of the struggle,

901
02:31:09,747 --> 02:31:17,735
[SPEAKER_11]: for genuine equality and that is where we are getting the resistance because there was never intention to go this far.

902
02:31:18,636 --> 02:31:24,482
[SPEAKER_11]: People were reacting to Bull Connor or reacting to Jim Clark rather than acting in good faith.

903
02:31:25,082 --> 02:31:27,804
[SPEAKER_11]: to realization of genuine equality.

904
02:31:27,864 --> 02:31:33,989
[SPEAKER_11]: And Bill Conner, if you remember, ordered the use of hoses on the students that were marching.

905
02:31:34,770 --> 02:31:40,515
[SPEAKER_11]: And Jim Clark was the sheriff who did the violent arrest of civil rights protesters during Selma.

906
02:31:42,753 --> 02:31:45,677
[SPEAKER_11]: He was also reflecting on his I Have a Dream speech.

907
02:31:45,777 --> 02:31:53,366
[SPEAKER_11]: And during that period of the movement, he said, there was a great period of solid, a solid decade of progress.

908
02:31:54,047 --> 02:31:58,412
[SPEAKER_11]: And that dream, he said, at many points since then has turned into a nightmare.

909
02:31:59,113 --> 02:32:15,005
[SPEAKER_11]: And so he admitted that he was very overly optimistic, but while he still had hope and faith in this country, this now needed to be tempered with the solid realism that we still have a long way to go.

910
02:32:15,025 --> 02:32:21,150
[SPEAKER_11]: So I'm gonna focus on this response because we do still have a long way to go.

911
02:32:21,630 --> 02:32:27,495
[SPEAKER_11]: This felt surreal to me because we're going through this very similar circumstances today.

912
02:32:28,115 --> 02:32:31,817
[SPEAKER_11]: We're still fighting for equality in the world that we want to see.

913
02:32:32,837 --> 02:32:46,083
[SPEAKER_11]: As I think about where we are in our society today, the polarization, the blatant racism, sexism language, this should be appalling and unacceptable to all of us.

914
02:32:47,003 --> 02:32:49,305
[SPEAKER_11]: In addition, we have ongoing wars.

915
02:32:49,445 --> 02:32:51,547
[SPEAKER_11]: Democracy is under attack.

916
02:32:51,647 --> 02:32:53,429
[SPEAKER_11]: Voting rights are under attack.

917
02:32:53,549 --> 02:32:55,711
[SPEAKER_11]: Reproductive rights are under attack.

918
02:32:56,152 --> 02:32:59,615
[SPEAKER_11]: Diversity, equity, and inclusion is under attack.

919
02:33:00,115 --> 02:33:02,657
[SPEAKER_11]: Critical race theory is under attack.

920
02:33:02,697 --> 02:33:09,423
[SPEAKER_11]: And as a result, we have legislators debating bills and states banning books from schools.

921
02:33:10,184 --> 02:33:15,165
[SPEAKER_11]: The Supreme Court struck down the affirmative action and admission policies for colleges.

922
02:33:15,845 --> 02:33:23,947
[SPEAKER_11]: Folks, structural and institutional racism and white supremacy still exist and it is heightened more than ever.

923
02:33:24,667 --> 02:33:31,029
[SPEAKER_11]: When progress is made, white supremacists plot and attempt to take away the progress that we have made.

924
02:33:31,429 --> 02:33:39,831
[SPEAKER_11]: It is the very same thing that Dr. King was talking about 58 years ago, the white backlash.

925
02:33:40,431 --> 02:33:44,415
[SPEAKER_11]: Sadly, today, the words of Dr. King is still alive.

926
02:33:44,495 --> 02:33:56,605
[SPEAKER_11]: He said, I have a dream that my four little children will live in a nation where they will not be judged by the color of their skin, but by the content of their character.

927
02:33:56,625 --> 02:34:01,790
[SPEAKER_11]: This really puts it in a nutshell for me on what we're still fighting for.

928
02:34:02,510 --> 02:34:11,097
[SPEAKER_11]: So how do we individually and collectively continue the struggle to realize the dream that Dr. King had?

929
02:34:11,577 --> 02:34:15,981
[SPEAKER_11]: And I would hope that all of us in this room want to see that happen.

930
02:34:16,862 --> 02:34:20,685
[SPEAKER_11]: We can start by developing our own individual blueprint.

931
02:34:21,385 --> 02:34:34,049
[SPEAKER_11]: Begin by defining and developing your own values, what you need as an individual, what is the kind of life that you want to achieve, the kind of friends that you should be with, what does success look like?

932
02:34:34,630 --> 02:34:39,972
[SPEAKER_11]: Dr. King talked about a commitment to the eternal principle of beauty, love, and justice.

933
02:34:40,312 --> 02:34:45,013
[SPEAKER_11]: What is your commitment to advocating for social and racial justice?

934
02:34:45,453 --> 02:34:49,255
[SPEAKER_11]: What are the ways in which you will fight for a just society?

935
02:34:50,215 --> 02:34:56,698
[SPEAKER_11]: After we develop our blueprint, we can talk with others and see who we are aligned with, who's aligned with our values.

936
02:34:57,259 --> 02:35:18,890
[SPEAKER_11]: And from my perspective, the basic principle to understand the need for common decency and where we can collectively move the needle in addressing systemic racism and barriers that prevent us from our fullest potential and to hold America accountable, to live up to its ideal.

937
02:35:19,730 --> 02:35:21,651
[SPEAKER_11]: We should focus on our communities.

938
02:35:22,171 --> 02:35:23,911
[SPEAKER_11]: Be active in our communities.

939
02:35:24,351 --> 02:35:26,072
